In 741 CE ({{ill|Tenpyō 13|ja|天平|12=draft}}), he was appointed Governor of {{ill|Inaba Province|ja|Inaba Province|12=draft}}, at which time he held the rank of {{ill|Jugo-i no Ge|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft}}. He was promoted several times in subsequent years, including: - {{ill|Jugo-i no Jō|ja|従五位上|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|12=draft}} in 743 CE. - {{ill|Shogo-i no Ge|ja|正五位下|1=Senior Fifth Rank|lt=Senior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft}} in 749 CE, when he also became Assistant Minister of the {{ill|Hyōbu-shō|ja|兵部省|12=draft}}. - Governor of {{ill|Kazusa Province|ja|上総国|12=draft}} in 754 CE.
In 757 CE, Inagimi was promoted to {{ill|Shogo-i no Jō|ja|正五位上|1=Senior Fifth Rank|lt=Senior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|12=draft}} in May. Following the suppression of the {{ill|Tachibana no Naramaro Rebellion|ja|橘奈良麻呂の乱|12=draft}} in August of the same year, he was further elevated to {{ill|Jushi-i|ja|従四位下|lt=Junior Fourth Rank, Lower Grade|1=Junior Fourth Rank|12=draft}} for his contributions.
In 758 CE, while serving as Governor of Yamato Province, Inagimi reported the discovery of a set of 16 characters carved into the roots of a wisteria tree at {{ill|Miwa Mountain|ja|三輪山|12=draft}} in {{ill|Shikijō District|ja|城下郡|12=draft}}. These characters were interpreted as a divine affirmation of {{ill|Fujiwara no Nakamaro|ja|藤原仲麻呂|12=draft}}'s governance.<ref>{{Cite Shoku Nihongi|date=Tenpyō Hōji 2, 27th day of the 2nd month}}</ref>
